B. Conduct the following analysis on the numerical (interval and ratio attributes):

i. Pair plots to look for possible clusters

  • It's not practical to draw pair plots for all 64 columns, which will generate 64 * 64 / 2 = 2048 scatter plots.
  • We will use correlation heatmap to check the correlations between attrs, and try drawing pair plots for principal components.
In[14]:
corr_matrix = df_transformed[numerical_attrs].corr()
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))
sns.heatmap(corr_matrix)
plt.show()

Use PCA to reduce dimensionality to 5:

In[15]:
pca_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('standard_scaler', StandardScaler()),
    ('PCA', PCA(n_components=5))
])

df_copy = df_transformed[numerical_attrs].copy()
pca_components = pca_pipeline.fit_transform(df_copy)

pca_df = pd.DataFrame(data=pca_components, columns=['PC1', 'PC2', 'PC3', 'PC4', 'PC5'])
In[16]:
sns.pairplot(pca_df, diag_kind = 'kde')
plt.show()

Try reducing dimensionality to 3:

In[17]:
pca_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('standard_scaler', StandardScaler()),
    ('PCA', PCA(n_components=3))
])

df_copy = df_transformed[numerical_attrs].copy()
pca_components = pca_pipeline.fit_transform(df_copy)

pca_df = pd.DataFrame(data=pca_components, columns=['PC1', 'PC2', 'PC3'])
In[18]:
sns.pairplot(pca_df, diag_kind = 'kde')
plt.show()

Try reducing dimensionality to 2:

In[19]:
pca_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('standard_scaler', StandardScaler()),
    ('PCA', PCA(n_components=2))
])

df_copy = df_transformed[numerical_attrs].copy()
pca_components = pca_pipeline.fit_transform(df_copy)

pca_df = pd.DataFrame(data=pca_components, columns=['PC1', 'PC2'])
In[20]:
sns.scatterplot(pca_df, x='PC1', y='PC2')
plt.show()

Try UMAP as the non-linear dimension reduction method:

In[21]:
from umap import UMAP

umap_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('standard_scaler', StandardScaler()),
    ('UMAP', UMAP(n_components=2))
])

df_copy = df_transformed[numerical_attrs].copy()
umap_components = umap_pipeline.fit_transform(df_copy)

umap_df = pd.DataFrame(data=umap_components, columns=['UMAP1', 'UMAP2'])
In[22]:
sns.scatterplot(umap_df, x='UMAP1', y='UMAP2')
plt.show()

ii. Histograms to look for possible clusters

In[23]:
plt.figure(figsize=(24, 24))

for i, attr in enumerate(numerical_attrs):
    plt.subplot(8, 8, i+1)
    sns.histplot(df_transformed[attr], kde=True)

plt.show()
  • From above plots, it seems distinct grouping cannot be easily found. Also, the variance within attrs are relatively uniform, which adds the difficulty to find distinct clusters.
  • In the next phase, we will try tuning the UMAP hyperparameters, or try more different algorithms like K-Means to find the clusters.
